 "hero.kicker": "Agent Platform · Single Go Binary · Open Source Coming Soon",
 "hero.title": "The agent platform,<br/><span class=\"accent\">set in metal type.</span>",
 "hero.sub": "Jikji is a modular agent framework that runs as one static Go binary — a deterministic agent loop, durable orchestration state, adaptive multi-model coordination, and built-in governance. Built for long-horizon agentic workflows, from a laptop to enterprise clusters.",
 "cta.start": "Get Started",
 "cta.github": "GitHub — Coming Soon",
 "hero.note": "This site is written from the code as it is being implemented today — Jikji is under active development, and details may change before the first release.",
 "story.tag": "The Name",
 "story.h2": "Named after the world's first movable metal type book",
 "story.p1": "<b>Jikji</b> (직지심체요절) was printed in Korea in 1377 — the oldest surviving book printed with movable metal type, decades before Gutenberg. Movable type changed publishing the same way Jikji aims to change agents: <b>composable pieces, set precisely, producing reliable output at scale.</b>",
 "story.p2": "Every module carries a letterpress name — the <b>foundry</b> casts the runtime, <b>type</b> faces the models, <b>sorts</b> are the tools, the <b>compositor</b> sets sessions, the <b>forme</b> locks the agent loop, and the <b>press</b> serves it to the world. Even the default port is <span class=\"mono\">1377</span>.",
 "story.cap": "Jikjisimcheyojeol — the oldest extant book printed with movable metal type. UNESCO Memory of the World.",
 "nav.why": "Why Jikji",
 "why.h2": "What makes it different from other agent frameworks",
 "why.p": "Most agent frameworks are Python or Node.js/TypeScript libraries glued to a vector DB, with opaque loops and governance bolted on later. Jikji is built like infrastructure from day one.",
 "c1.h": "One static binary, zero dependency hell",
 "c1.p": "Written in Go and shipped as a single static binary. No Python or Node.js toolchains, no dependency conflicts. The same binary runs on your laptop, as split services, or in a multi-node cluster.",
 "c1.more": "See the architecture →",
 "c2.h": "A deterministic, recoverable agent loop",
 "c2.p": "The <code>forme</code> loop models every step as explicit actions and observations — with checkpointing and recovery built into the engine. Agent runs are replayable and auditable, not opaque chains that vanish on crash.",
 "c2.more": "Inside the loop →",
 "c3.h": "Adaptive multi-model orchestration",
 "c3.p": "Run a swarm of models that debate and revise, gate the synthesis behind a verifier panel, and let the <code>trinity</code> coordinator learn which model to route each turn to — an evolved policy, not a fixed schedule.",
 "c3.more": "How orchestration works →",
 "c4.h": "Memory that learns, context that fits",
 "c4.p": "The <code>plate</code> memory plane extracts facts, consolidates them in background \"dreaming\" passes, and serves hybrid recall. Context compaction and a model-promotion ladder keep long runs inside the window.",
 "c4.more": "Memory &amp; data →",
 "c5.h": "Governance built in, not bolted on",
 "c5.p": "Multi-tenancy, scoped API keys, RBAC, a dynamic policy filter chain with approval gates, structured audit, and PII/secret redaction — all in the core, with a vault for credentials and OAuth provider wiring.",
 "c5.more": "Enterprise &amp; security →",
 "c6.h": "Open protocols, no lock-in",
 "c6.p": "Serves an OpenAI-compatible API and speaks MCP (server and client), ACP, and A2A for agent-to-agent collaboration. Works with OpenAI-, Anthropic-, Ollama-, and GLM/Z.AI-compatible backends.",
 "c6.more": "Protocols &amp; surfaces →",
 "exp.tag": "Explore the platform",
 "exp.h2": "Six planes, one press",
 "exp.p": "Each plane owns one concern behind a strict boundary. Follow any of them into the detail.",
 "exp.arch.h": "Architecture",
 "exp.arch.p": "A print shop of composable modules, deployment shapes from one process to a grid, galley-backed storage, and the binaries that run it.",
 "exp.more": "Read more →",
 "exp.loop.h": "Agent loop",
 "exp.loop.p": "The deterministic <code>forme</code> loop — checkpoints and resume, Lua hooks, verify-revise synthesis, goal-driven runs, and a self-improving harness.",
 "exp.more2": "Read more →",
 "exp.tools.h": "Tools",
 "exp.tools.p": "A broad built-in catalog — files, shell, a DOM-extracting browser, SQL, ontology — run under a sandbox, over MCP, or on remote nodes, plus Lua/Python functions as tools.",
 "exp.more7": "Read more →",
 "exp.orch.h": "Orchestration",
 "exp.orch.p": "Multi-model swarms, the evolved <code>trinity</code> coordinator, delegation to sub-agents, and A2A federation across peers.",
 "exp.more3": "Read more →",
 "exp.mem.h": "Memory &amp; data",
 "exp.mem.p": "Cognitive memory with dreaming, hybrid recall, context and token optimization, and SQLite/PostgreSQL/MySQL backends.",
 "exp.more4": "Read more →",
 "exp.onto.h": "Ontology engine",
 "exp.onto.p": "A native engine that builds knowledge graphs from a corpus and serves them with in-process SPARQL — an ontology over your data, with no external triple store.",
 "exp.more6": "Read more →",
 "exp.ent.h": "Enterprise &amp; security",
 "exp.ent.p": "Tenancy, RBAC and the policy plane, vault and OAuth, OpenTelemetry tracing, usage limits, redaction, injection defense, and robustness.",
 "exp.more5": "Read more →",
